<l>vāḻiya veṉṉuñ ceyaveṉ kiḷavi</l>
<l>yiṟuti yakaraṅ keṭutalu murittē</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">Aṉṉa,</foreign> the particle of comparison,<note
              place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">uvamakkiḷavi.</foreign></note></l>
<l>vocative words<note
              place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">viḷinilaikkiḷavi.</foreign></note> addressed [to persons] near,</l>
<l>finite verbs of the type <foreign xml:lang="ta">ceymmaṉa,</foreign></l>
<l>optative<note
              place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">viyaṅkōṭkiḷavi.</foreign></note> in the sense of command,<note
              place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">ēval.</foreign></note></l>
<l>relative participles<note
              place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">peyareñcukiḷavi.</foreign></note> of the type <foreign xml:lang="ta">ceyta,</foreign></l>
<l>gerunds of the type <foreign xml:lang="ta">ceyyiya,</foreign></l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">amma,</foreign> the particle used in addressing [a person]</l>
<l>and the words ending in <foreign xml:lang="ta">-a</foreign> denoting many -</l>
<l>all these, they say, remain unchanged.<note
              place="foot">Exx. : 1. <foreign xml:lang="ta">poṉ aṉṉa kutirai 2. ūra </foreign>(voc. of <foreign xml:lang="ta">ūraṉ) koḷ 3. uṇmaṉa kutirai 4. celka kutirai 5. uṇṭa kutirai 6. uṇṇiya koṇṭāṉ 7. amma koṟṟā 8. pala kutirai.</foreign></note></l>
      </lg>
